@node MAIN "editingtagfile.html"
     How to change the tagfiles     How to change the tagfiles  

Tag-o-Miga supports two different broad types of tagfiles. These are 'multi-line' and 'one-line' taglines/files.  Multi-line  

As the name suggests, multi-line taglines can be many lines long. In theory this allows a single tagline to be as long as you want, but you'll probably find various users and moderators jumping for your throat if you repeatedly use taglines longer than three lines or so!  

There are three variants of this format, which Tag-o-Miga refers to as Fortune, Spot and Cyclone files. The only difference between them is the 'delimiter' -- Fortune uses %, Spot uses %% and Cyclone uses %%%.  

The first line of the tagfile must be an [OPT] line containing either FORTUNE, SPOT or CYCLONE. If you omit the tagfile type, then the default type specified in the preferences will be assumed.  

Each tagline may be as long you want. The end of a tagline is marked by a line containing the delimiter described above. For example, a Spot file might look like:   
    [OPT] SPOT 
    First tagline 
    %% 
    Second tagline 
    %% 
    Third tagline 
    %% 
    Last tagline  One-line  

One-line tagfiles contain taglines which are all one line long. As Tag-o-Miga knows the exact length of each tagline, it does not need %% or any other delimeter to indicate when one tagline ends and the next begins.  

To let Tag-o-Miga know that a file contains one-liners, either it must begin with the line [OPT] ONELINE, or Oneliner is specified as the default tagfile type in the preferences. An example tagfile would therefore be:      [OPT] ONELINE 
    First tagline 
    Second tagline 
    Third tagline 
    Last tagline  Special commands  

A number of special commands are available. These are as follows:  

; (semicolon) - this indicates a comment. This not appear in Tag-o-Miga's GUI or be chosen randomly.  

[COMMENT] - the rest of the line is a comment. These comment lines will appear in the tag window. Tag-o-Miga will not randomly pick a [COMMENT] line.  

[ALTLIST] - the rest of the line is the filename of another tagfile. If this tagline is selected, either randomly by Tag-o-Miga or manually from the tag window, then that tagfile is loaded in.  Example tagfiles  

First, a multi-line example:      [OPT] SPOT 
    ; Richard's tagline file 
    First tagline 
    %% 
    [COMMENT] The 'Borg' taglines 
    I am Superconductor of Borg.  Resistance is futile. 
    %% 
    [ALTLIST]RedDwarfTags.txt 
    %% 
    Last tagline  

Now, a one-line example:      [OPT] ONELINE 
    ; Richard's tagline file 
    First tagline 
    [COMMENT] The 'Borg' taglines 
    I am Superconductor of Borg.  Resistance is futile. 
    [ALTLIST]RedDwarfTags.txt 
    Last tagline  The [OPT] line  

As you have seen, tagfiles can start with an [OPT] line. In addition to specifying the tagfile type, you can also specify the following options:       
         	INDEX, NOINDEX         	These options enable or disable tagfile indexing.         Indexing can speed up tagfile accesses when you have         large tagfiles. Indexing is not available on DOS due to         filename restrictions.          
         	BUFFER, NOBUFFER         	These options are now deprecated.  Buffering will be 	activated automatically if required and if there is 	enough memory to do so.        
	----------------------------------------
  

